Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among the stars related, that is, originated from a single cluster.
The results of their research have been published in the journal Nature, and they can be briefly found on the university’s website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearest stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, which precedes the formation of stars.
Even if a born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of relatives stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The modeling results carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts used a supercomputer to model two streams of interstellar gas that together formed the cloud.
Over the course of several million years, this object under the influence of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added label paints to the initial gas flows and found that a high degree of chemical homogeneity is achieved thanks to rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to search for stars-related by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
