Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that protects trade unions as a civil right.
“Where unions are, there are middle-class jobs,” says Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota who is a co-chair of the Progressive Party Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to present the Workers’ Rights Enhancement Act along with the symbol of the civil rights movement, John Lewis.
This ground-breaking bill will give workers the same legal opportunities when discriminating against trade unions as it does in other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of opponents of trade unions.
Amendments to the Labour Relations Act to allow workers who are discriminated against for participating in trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and penalties - are a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is undoubtedly not a radical initiative – at least according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are suggesting is to remember the very American idea.
Despite the attacks on trade unions in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans have once supported countries around the world to embrace, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organization at the same time.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in forming a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly acknowledged that "the right of workers to organize, to negotiate and to collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations with the aim of protecting and improving working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to impair this right will have no legal effect; measures aimed at these ends will be found to be unlawful.
When the former First Lady of Eleanor Roosevelt was president of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global agreement, Roosevelt and the organizers had the right to include the guarantee that "the
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labour rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to trade unions — and to have this union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — should be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to be organized and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but has increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and elevated the entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as well.
The official recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the enhancement of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against trade unions - has long been ripe.
Keith Allison and John Lewis revive the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
A judge temporarily blocks a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the Louisiana law, which supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed for execution by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginald in June and was due to enter into force on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to hospitalize patients within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that at the moment, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally, continuing to act to obtain authority,” Judge John deGravells wrote in his decision.
The hearing will be appointed within the month in which the judge will make a more permanent decision under this law.
Defenders of the right to abortion happily welcomed this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to receive hospital authorizations.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from the insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit to suspend the law on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who did not act as plaintiffs in the case and also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed such laws, and courts have recently found such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would have closed most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admissions laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion objected that such measures were aimed at protecting women’s health, although some also noted their positive effect on the closure of clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admissions authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish abortion doctors as long as their applications for admissions authority await a decision.
