Lack of timely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who fast in Australia’s rural areas face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those who live in cities.
The researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan from the QIMR Berghofer Institute of Medical Research said that the risk of dying during the study was 20 percent higher in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than in those living in urban areas.
NEEDED SURVEY: New Drugs May Slow Down Lung and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers tracked the medical path of women over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases, and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Women of older age and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
While the study was not designed to determine why women living outside of cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that a timely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of outbound services that will allow professionals to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Niv, said she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
