China's Biggest Companies Unite Against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China’s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messengers, etc.) and Baidu (China’s largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the wonder of the Chinese Internet, which has left even its American rivals - eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
The Union of the Largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% by each of the Internet companies, Wanda Group said in a statement.
It is planned to register a company in Hong Kong.
SP will combine Baidu’s search services with the popular social platform WeChat (China’s largest social network, with around 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda’s infrastructure.
