In addition, Wanda is owned by American cinema network AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its own shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, the development of which will be handled by the newly created competitor Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will head the new company, thanks to the merger, Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new site is set to become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, Dong Tse said.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O are coupon sales services such as Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the largest ‘cake’ in online commerce,” said Wanda Wang Jianlin, CEO of O2O.
"Now there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation everyone's chances are roughly equal," he said.
The Chinese e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and according to McKinsey & Co., its volume will increase more than three times by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has risen to 632 million, according to official statistics from Bloomberg: it is the largest population of any country in the world, except India.
By 2015, this number is expected to grow to 850 million people.
The Union of the Richest
Tencent Ma Huaten was China’s richest man until recently, but according to the Bloomberg Millionaire Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his share in Alibaba.
Baidu leader Robin Lee is now ranked third among China’s wealthiest people, while Wang Jianlin of Wanda is ranked fourth.
