But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after its creation: “Rome cannot be built in one day.”
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only for new companies, but also for the well-deserved leaders of the world of online commerce, is evidenced by the aforementioned report on Alibaba’s financial performance for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as something of an average between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company earned more than its two U.S. competitors combined.
Alibaba’s net profit for the period nearly doubles the same sum of competitors – it grew nearly three times year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has enormous potential for generating money, largely due to its mobile applications,” said Bloomberg analyst from Hong Kong’s Arete Research Service.
According to Alibaba’s updated prospectus on the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission’s website, the number of active mobile users of the company’s services in July was 188 million, significantly above the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the past quarter came from mobile devices.
Alibaba is going to name the value of its shares before the IPO.
