President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Before the ceasefire agreement halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not go out or leave their homes, leaving for safer areas further away from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the border with Gaza, where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a piece of Palestinian mine, doubt that they should return.
The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families have not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at the time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the border with Gaza that was severely hit by Palestinian fire.
He advised children to study diligently and said, “We will do our best to give you the knowledge and ensure your safety.”
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite ceasefire on Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately put an end to hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas' demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its weapons and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect negotiations is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of whom were civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
The Israeli side killed 66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gazan militants fired 4,591 missiles and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, carried out more than 5,000 air strikes and other attacks.
As a result of the Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip were damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 250,000 people found shelter in more than 100 schools, which were converted into shelters.
Due to the fact that tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and the fighting continued, education officials postponed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza’s schools.
