Production growth in the euro area slowed to its lowest level in 13 months in August, according to a popular study.
The latest value of the Eurozone’s manufacturing sector’s Business Activity Index (PMI) fell to a mark of 50.7 in August, down from 51.8 in July.
A value above 50 indicates growth.
New orders were delayed, and enterprises suffered amid growing tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The figures came before the meeting of the European Central Bank (ECB) on Thursday.
Markets will wait from the bank for a clear plan on how to cope with stopping the recovery of the eurozone, as well as the threat of inflation deflation, which is only 0.3%.
There is a suggestion that ECB President Mario Draghi could give additional signals later this week that he is considering a quantitative easing scheme for the eurozone similar to those used by the UK and the US during the financial crisis.
“Although some growth is better than no growth at all, the dampening effect of growing economic and geopolitical uncertainty on producers is becoming more apparent,” said Rob Dobson, Markit’s senior economist.
The PMI of Germany’s manufacturing sector, Russia’s largest trading partner in the EU, fell to its lowest level in 11 months at 51.4.
Meanwhile, in France’s second-largest economy, the PMI fell to 46.9.
France continues to cause real concern, as does Italy’s weakening from steady growth to stagnation.
The signs that the momentum of growth has gone out in the main industrial engine, Germany, as well as in Spain and the Netherlands, also do not add to the confidence," Dobson said.
The slowdown in industry is likely to fuel analysts awaiting additional monetary or fiscal stimulus.
One positive news was from Ireland, where the PMI rose to 57.3, its highest level since the end of 1999.
Howard Archer, chief economist at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing to say about the August survey of the euro area manufacturing sector’s business activity index is that it shows that the sector is still growing.”
He added: “Producers in the eurozone are obviously finding life very difficult at the moment, as the current increased geopolitical tension – especially related to Russia / Ukraine – adds uncertainty to the still difficult conditions in many countries.
This increased tension has obviously hit business — and especially consumer confidence — and is likely leading to some orders being delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
