Twitter tries to be more interesting for new users
Twitter’s microblogging service has changed the user registration process to engage new members more quickly in active interaction with the platform.
This measure should reduce the number of people who have abandoned their microblogging.
Now, new Twitter users will browse a large number of the service’s recommended accounts while signing up to instantly make up their reading circle.
Recommendations are drawn up on the basis of the interests indicated when registering.
At the same time, Twitter automatically sets a subscription tick for all automatically selected accounts.
Due to this, the user will have to remove the check marks manually, so as not to read those who are not interested in them.
If previously users of the microblogging service saw only the avatars of recommended users, now Twitter is taking a sample of one of the blogger’s popular tweets to help make an impression on a person.
This is the biggest change in Twitter’s registration page in three years.
Recently, Twitter has been actively working on upgrading the service.
Such activity is primarily associated with the continued efforts of the service to achieve losslessness.
In 2014, the microblogging service faced a slowdown in the growth of the user base and a decline in reader activity.
The company is desperately in need of more loyal consumers who, once there, would stay for a long time.
This is the only way to ensure a steady flow of advertising resources.
