Vehicle Recycling Program Renewed on September 1st
From September 1 in Russia, the program for the recycling of cars is renewed.
By December 31, 2014, 10 billion rubles will be allocated for these purposes.
As explained by the head of the Ministry of Commerce of the Russian Federation Denis Manturov, the money is allocated from the limits, which have already been brought to the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation by redistribution from other directions of support.
The program will affect all cars older than six years.
The amount of compensation will be from 40 thousand for a car to 350,000 rubles for a truck.
Earlier in Russia, a similar program of recycling of cars was already in place.
The main difference of the current project, the minister explained, is that now it is assumed not only the use of machines to get a subsequent discount, but also the possibility, if the car has reached the age of six years, to buy a new one with a discount when the old one is handed over to the dealer, reports Interfax.
More than 16 billion rubles were spent on the previous federal recycling program, which ran from January 1, 2010 to December 31, 2011.
Thanks to it, the level of production of passenger cars in 2010 amounted to about 1.2 million pieces (that is, plus 101.4% compared to 2009).
The creator of Coming Out Simulator will release a game about modern journalism
Game designer Nicky Case, known for the game Coming Out Simulator decided to release a game about modern journalism.
He spoke about his project in an interview with Kill Screen.
Case started working on the game a few weeks ago, but this fact is only now widely known.
The inspiration for the game came from events in Ferguson, where protests are now taking place, which began after a police officer killed an unarmed black teenager.
The focus of the project, which does not yet have a title, will be how the information coverage of the stories affects their consequences.
The hero of the game, a civilian journalist, will need to photograph what is happening in areas where clashes between the police and the population take place.
The hero can differently photograph what is happening, which will affect the course of events.
If he shoots the scene so that the policemen will look like heroes and the protesters like gangsters, the police will start to treat him better and let him go where the ordinary person cannot go.
If he will shed light on the events differently, his photographs could turn peaceful protests into a large-scale rebellion.
The points in the game will need to be scored with the help of the hero's twitter, in which new subscribers will appear if the photos posted there are popular.
The game has no name yet.
The date of its release and the platform on which it will appear are unknown.
Case, however, has published an image showing how an event can change depending on how the photo is taken and processed about it.
In an interview with Kill Screen, Case explained that he had been thinking about the concept of such a game for quite some time, but initially wanted to dedicate it not to protests in the US, but to events in the Gaza Strip.
After he started collecting material for the game, the game designer realized that he lacked the knowledge and skills to shed light on the history of the region.
However, when he saw the media covering the events in Ferguson, he decided to make a game based on what had happened.
Nicky Case is an independent developer who releases browser games.
His most famous project was Coming Out Simulator, released in 2014.
This game, which tells about events from Case's biography, is dedicated to how a bisexual teenager tries to tell his homophobic parents about his relationship.
