The army controls the new government of Thailand
General Prayut (right) appointed Right Wongswan (left) as Defense Minister
The military ruler and prime minister of Thailand, General Prayut Chan-ocha, has announced the formation of a new cabinet of ministers in which more than a third of the posts are held by retired generals or generals.
Representatives of the army received key positions: ministers of defense, finance, foreign affairs and trade.
On Monday, Prayut Chan-ocha was formally approved as prime minister after the king of Thailand formally approved the appointment of the head of the interim military government to the post.
The 60-year-old soldier, who seized power in the country as a result of a bloodless coup on May 22, was the only candidate for prime minister.
He was elected Prime Minister at a meeting of Parliament.
Earlier, the army appointed deputies to parliament.
According to Prayuta Chan-ocha, the coup was the only way to maintain stability.
He was preceded by a six-year-long demonstration during which protesters demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Yinglak Chinawat’s government.
Prayut Chan-ocha will officially be the interim prime minister as the military plans to hold a general election in late 2015.
However, there are concerns that the military is trying to strengthen its power in the country.
The military came to power on May 22.
It is a complete paralysis of civil power.
The leaders of the main political parties were subjected to temporary arrest.
Immediately after the military came to power, they temporarily arrested the country’s leading politicians, including Prime Minister Yinglyk Chinawat.
Some journalists and public figures were also arrested.
The current political crisis has its roots in 2006, when the army dismissed Brother Yinglyk Chinavat Taksin as prime minister.
Both are popular among the rural population, especially in the northern parts of the country, which has ensured their success in elections.
However, many representatives of the middle class and the capital elite have joined an anti-government movement that has virtually paralyzed the country since November 2013.
