Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
The British woman said she spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karen Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking that she had only a few years left to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Sharko-Mari-Tuta disease (SMT), a group of hereditary disorders that lead to damage to nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK has reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with MTS because so little is known about this condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have an MTS, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure walking, and pressed toes.
Patients may experience numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, meaning that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrich's ataxia, a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be tied to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and she would die before she was 30.
The mother of two, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others could.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I was never able to ride a roller or skateboard with other kids, and I was a lot bullied at school because of how I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at the medical record when her doctor left the room and it was written that she had an AF.
"I felt guilty because I put my nose where it shouldn't go, and so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library, and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in this interval.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just got up, hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease, because you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that poses a far lesser threat to your life.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have an MTS.
“When he explained what the SMT was, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK’s SMT charity has announced a month of information on SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The tax burden on entrepreneurs in the Washington area increases as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose moderately last year as the economy accelerated recovery, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia paid $27.6 billion to the state and local treasury in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden on business per state and local level rose by 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, compared with 3.9 percent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when bills declined, in 2009 and 2010.
Taxes levied by the state grew faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by the professional services firm, Ernst & Young and the State Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenues, 56 percent, come from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenues come from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the least amount of tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
The rise in tax revenues is largely driven by a return to companies’ previous real estate value levels, researchers say, raising real estate taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row when growth was less than 1 percent.
While much of this revenue comes from large states such as California, New York, and Texas, it seems the same is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, up $9.6 billion from 2012—an increase of 4.2 percent over the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate has no similar effect on tax revenue growth across the state and local levels in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies’ tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of the state and local tax bills in the form of real estate taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a non-profit organization that doesn’t pay real estate taxes,” Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Tax Center, said in a statement.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the restoration of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurial incomes also seem to be going up, according to these figures.
Companies in the region have declared a state-wide corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, up $2.1 billion from 2012.
Maryland has collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although the trends are in one direction, the tax burden for entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three locations.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the country average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues have risen below the average of 4.1 per cent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high - 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia had lower taxes for business owners per state and local level and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for business owners than in Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed a bill lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to achieve its tax revenue targets next year, the law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to even 3% by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be feeling better and thus paying more taxes on the state and local level, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneur taxes paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners - the transitional structure under which the majority of small firms are organized - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose by 20 percent last year to more than $2.4 billion.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country are likely to continue this year, with revenues from turnover tax in state and local governments rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may be lagging behind, as a reduction in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
