MEPs proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
In case of success of the initiative, the data of the Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The State Duma has introduced a draft law that provides for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is based on the legislative activities of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Fair Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, in the opinion of the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more expeditious and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the protection of personal data and the observance of the secret of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, which hastens parliamentarians to enter into force, obliges to store personal data of Russians processed via the Internet on the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes mandatory the recording, systematization, storage, storage, clarification and extraction of personal data of Russian citizens, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as the indication of the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of violators of websites - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects".
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugova and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the KPRF.
Djengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current draft law on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation, will have to pay for the rent
Commenting on the draft law submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy, Leonid Levin, said that he does not see any problems with the transfer of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storage of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "to Rostelecom", which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, to GroupMail.
"In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
“If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the Russian Federation, I see no problem – they will get technological opportunities for accommodation,” Levin said.
The Disputed Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Electronic Communications Association expressed concern that if the bill is passed, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for flights and hotels.
According to the association, "the draft law deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data, determining imperatively that their registration, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
The RAEC statement stressed that a more effective measure would be the establishment of a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is being carried out and to systematize his personal data.
In this case, you will be able to choose on which territory these actions will take place.
The adoption of similar bills on the “localization” of personal data in other countries has led to the loss of global services and significant economic losses.
