The required literature for last semester would have cost $430, he says.
He spent $120.
According to the College Council, the average student spends more than $1,200 a year on textbooks and study supplies, but students have a number of options to reduce these costs.
Students are increasingly choosing online stores and creative ideas similar to the Schroeder system.
Book rental is becoming increasingly popular, allowing students to use the book during the semester, and often costs considerably less than their purchase.
Nibo Incorporated, which owns more than 250 university bookstores, reports that the volume of book rentals has doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of books in university bookstores during the last spring semester were rented out, says Nibo Vice President Trevor Meyer.
Less than half of all books are purchased in university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here is an introductory course on the best ways to make a profitable deal.
Shopping in the online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book may be one-third of what you’ll see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of "Mathematical Analysis" by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler costs about $290 per price, but the new copy can be purchased for $239.99 at Chegg.com, which specializes in selling textbooks.
Buying a used
If you’re not against someone else’s marks or damage, used textbooks are a good option.
"Mathematical Analysis" is sold for $93.49 in second-hand form on Chegg.com.
Matt Caseday, 25, a fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a second-hand copy of the booklet Strategic Media Solutions: Understanding the Business Side of Advertising Business.
The book was sold for $48.
Lecturers such as Ingrid Bracey, director of the Wallless College at the University of Massachusetts at Emherst, invite students to clarify with their professors whether they can use previous editions.
Sometimes updates are insignificant for classes.
In such cases, old editions can often be found for a very small share of the cost of the last edition.
In addition to Chegg and Amazon sites, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative to buying used books.
Renting
It is worth thinking about renting textbooks, if you are good enough to handle them, do not forget to return them and do not want to keep them for yourself after the course is finished.
You can save more than 80% of the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent "Mathematical Analysis" for about $20 per semester.
Find out the rules of the store where you pick up the books, including any fines that may be imposed on you for markings, underscores, and damages.
If you are renting a book, remember: if you do not return the book, fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually leased by acquiring an electronic license for a certain period of time from distributors such as Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes & Noble Inc.
“Mathematical Analysis” on Chegg.com for six months will cost about $61.
Bracey says that students studying literature can often find the most affordable prices, as many classic works can now be downloaded for free, while literature on natural and engineering sciences can be quite expensive.
No matter what, take a look.
