SKR suspends investigation into Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Russian Investigative Committee (SKR) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was taken in connection with the death of the aircraft commander and the flight engineer.
The forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of entry to the landing, non-compliance of the crew with the standard procedures on the landing, as well as the unintentional exit of the engines at increased direct thrust speeds.
The Red Wings Tu-204 plane, which followed the Prague-Moscow flight, crashed on December 29, 2012, when it landed at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft rolled over the runway and ignited.
At the scene of the incident, an aircraft commander, a second pilot and a flight engineer were killed.
Two on-board escorts were taken to medical facilities, where they subsequently died from injuries.
Three other flight attendants, who were hospitalized with serious bodily injuries, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, who was moving at the time of the crash on the Kiev highway, received serious bodily injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The Transportation Prosecutor's Office carried out an inspection at the Red Wings after the accident, during which numerous violations were detected.
In February 2013, the airline's license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
