Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of human beings.
Angry facial expression is biologically universal to humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not random, but is an additional means of expression of power and threat, researchers from Australia and the United States found.
They told about their findings in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release from the University of California at Santa Barbara.
The expression of anger on the face is offset and dropped down the eyebrows, stretched into a thin line of lips, swollen nostrils are the same in all cultures, and are made even by birth blind children who have never seen it, says lead author Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that this emotion arose to effectively conduct disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he brings it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
Researchers have found confirmation of another of their hypotheses: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and go to the practice, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavourable conditions on others, and also prefer forceful methods of resolving conflicts peacefully.
Drawing on the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining,” the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that create the angry expression of the face should represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor – and thus cause the conflict conditions to agree with him as soon as possible.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated on a computer the faces where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or absent, and showed them to informers.
Although the lowered eyebrows or protruding chins did not individually make the face angry, the study participants unanimously recognized the physically stronger person depicted with such traits.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own power, forcing one to agree and obey.
A person inflates the nostrils and presses the lips for the same purpose as a frog that is inflated, or a baboon that shows its claws.
Anger is triggered by the interlocutor’s refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that most effectively demonstrates the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tuby.
Ministry of Communications has proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV radio company "Crimea"
In 2014, the Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget to the autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradiocompany "Crimea"".
This is stated in the draft resolution of the government, prepared by the agency, which was familiarized with "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment".
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to reequip the hardware and studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of the fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
The grants will be provided within the limits of the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
State broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959, broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the TV signal coverage of the TV radio company makes up more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011 "Teleradiokompanija "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
